04630nam a22007695i 9780231508919DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2008026477  a97802315089197 a10.7312/chen134842doi  a(DE-B1597)458739  a(OCoLC)979739265  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aRM217b.C44 2009 4aRM217b.C44 2009eb 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a615.8/542221 aChen, Nancy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFood, Medicine, and the Quest for Good Health :bNutrition, Medicine, and Culture /cNancy Chen. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (144 p.) :b7 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Rethinking Food and Medicine -- tPart One. Food as Medicine -- tOne. Healing Foods and Longevity -- tTwo. Dietary Prescriptions and Comfort Foods -- tPart Two. Medicine as Food -- tThree. Nutraceuticals and Functional Foods -- tFour. Genetically Modified Foods and Drugs -- tConclusion. Eating and Medicating -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat we eat, how we eat, where we eat, and when we eat are deeply embedded cultural practices. Eating is also related to how we medicate. The multimillion-dollar diet industry offers advice on how to eat for a better body and longer life, and avoiding harmful foods (or choosing healthy ones) is considered separate from consuming medicineanother multimillion-dollar industry. In contrast, most traditional medical systems view food as inseparable from medicine and regard medicinal foods as the front line of healing. Drawing on medical texts and food therapy practices from around the world and throughout history, Nancy N. Chen locates old and new crossovers between food and medicine in different social and cultural contexts. The consumption of spices, sugar, and salt was once linked to specific healing properties, and trade in these commodities transformed not just the political economy of Europe, Asia, and the New World but local tastes and food practices as well. Today's technologies are rapidly changing traditional attitudes toward food, enabling the cultivation of new admixtures, such as nutraceuticals and genetically modified food, that link food to medicine in novel ways. Chen considers these developments against the evolving food regimes of the diet industry in order to build a framework for understanding diet as individual practice, social prescription, and political formation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDiet therapyvSocial aspects. 0aDiet therapyxSocial aspects. 0aFood habits. 0aFunctional foodsvSocial aspects. 0aFunctional foodsxSocial aspects. 0aMedical anthropologyxSocial aspects. 0aMedical anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chen1348440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231508919423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231508919.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK